---
name: view-extraction
description: "Every <Name>Screen in iOS SwiftUI projects must expose a <Name>Content View — required for view tests via ViewInspector and for SwiftUI Previews without DI dependencies."
metadata:
  node_type: memory
  type: feedback
---

Every SwiftUI screen in {{PROJECT_NAME}} should be split into **two View structs**:

1. `<Name>Screen` — thin wrapper that owns the view model (`@StateObject`, `@ObservedObject`, or `@Bindable` for Observation). Receives navigation callbacks from parent.
2. `<Name>Content` — stateless View accepting concrete state and callbacks. **This** is what view tests (ViewInspector) target. Also makes SwiftUI Previews trivial.

**Why:** A View that internally constructs its own view model (e.g. via DI container resolution) cannot be:
- Tested with ViewInspector without setting up the full DI graph
- Previewed in Xcode without a working production-equivalent backend
- Embedded in other contexts (e.g. another module's preview) without leaking DI dependencies

Extracting a stateless `<Name>Content` fixes all three. Mirrors the Compose Screen/Content pattern (see `screen-content-extraction` in the Android counterpart project).

**How to apply:**

```swift
// Thin wrapper — gets the view model
struct ProfileScreen: View {
    @StateObject private var viewModel: ProfileViewModel = .resolve()

    var body: some View {
        ProfileContent(
            state: viewModel.state,
            onSave: viewModel.save,
            onCancel: viewModel.cancel
        )
    }
}

// Stateless body — testable, previewable
struct ProfileContent: View {
    let state: ProfileState
    let onSave: () -> Void
    let onCancel: () -> Void

    var body: some View {
        // ...
    }
}

#Preview {
    ProfileContent(
        state: .preview,
        onSave: {},
        onCancel: {}
    )
}
```

**Naming conventions:**
- `<Name>Screen` — outer, DI-aware
- `<Name>Content` — inner, stateless
- `<Name>State` (or `<Name>ViewState`) — the state struct passed in

**Reviewer check:** `{{PREFIX}}-reviewer-ios` Check 4 flags any new `*Screen.swift` without a corresponding `*Content` struct.

Related: [[testing-fakes-only]] (for unit ViewModel tests) and the `{{PREFIX}}-tester-ios` agent's "Test Type: view" section.
